<TITLE> UN nuclear terrorism pact to come into force </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 UNITED NATIONS, July 6 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A UN nuclear terrorism treaty that would oblige governments to punish those who illegally possess atomic devices or radioactive materials comes into force on Saturday. The accord, approved by the UN General Assembly in 2005, seven years after Russia first proposed it, is the first anti-terrorism convention completed since the Sept. 11, 2001, attacks on the United States. Bangladesh completed the treaty's requirement that 22 countries approve the pact before it could become law when the South Asian nation deposited its ratification papers with UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon last month. The pact, called the "International Convention for the Suppression of Acts of Nuclear Terrorism," is meant to stop clandestine networks from using or possessing nuclear weapons. It obligates governments to prosecute or extradite individuals who possess radioactive materials or nuclear devices or those who threaten others while possessing such materials. It aims to protect against attacks involving targets including nuclear power plants and reactors. The text also calls for exchanges of information and assistance among governments. Russia introduced the treaty in 1998 to keep "loose nukes" from falling into the hands of terrorist groups. Russia and other former Soviet republics have been cited as the most likely sources of black-market nuclear material. At the time, Alexander Lebed, then the Russian national security chief, said Moscow could not account for about 100 suitcase-sized nuclear weapons. Russia, however, is the only one of the nuclear weapons-holding permanent members of the UN Security Council so far to have ratified the convention. The other members are the United States, Britain, France and China. Of the world's other declared or assumed nuclear powers -- India, Pakistan and Israel -- only India has ratifi
